node.title: With the 2023 World Cup around the corner, 23 young A-League Women's players are hoping to make their mark
node.alt: Kyra Cooney-Cross and Leah Davidson have their eyes on the ball in the W-League
node.description: As the 2023 Women's World Cup approaches, the upcoming A-League Women's season is a chance for young players to make their mark. So who are some of the competition's most exciting prospects?
node.content: ["Australia's top professional women's competition has long been a greenhouse for producing some of the most exciting talent in world football.", "The A-League Women's former iteration, the W-League, was home to players like Sam Kerr, Kyah Simon, Steph Catley\u00a0and Alanna Kennedy, who would go on to play not only for the senior Matildas, but also for some of the biggest domestic clubs in the world like Chelsea, Arsenal, and Manchester City.", "So as the Australian competition enters its new, independent era under the Australian Professional Leagues, it has once again become the shop window for young, exciting players who could go on to become the next Kerr, Simon, Catley, or Kennedy.", "And with the 2023 Women's World Cup on the horizon, there are few seasons quite as important as this one for spotting the next big superstar who could make an impact on home soil in 18 months' time.", "So who are some of the young players to keep an eye on for the 2021/22 A-League Women's season?"]
